  "prompt": "What are the chances of the electoral college changing vote for Clinton?",
  "response": "The process of changing the outcome of a U.S. presidential election through the Electoral College is highly unlikely and has never happened. Electors are typically pledged to vote for the candidate who won their state's popular vote. While theoretically possible for so-called \"faithless electors\" to change their votes, the chances of a significant number doing so in order to alter the election outcome are extremely slim.\n\nFaithless electors are rare and often face penalties or are replaced with electors who will vote according to the state's popular vote. In addition, many states have laws binding electors to vote according to the state's results.\n\nHistorically, instances of faithless electors have not affected the overall outcome of a presidential election. Therefore, the chances of a substantial shift in the electoral vote from one candidate to another, such as changing votes to Clinton in a past election, are extremely low to non-existent.",
